s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Though shale gas has received considerable publicity, it remains to be seen what, if any, kind of unconventional gas technology could provide the economic and environmental benefits we expect for the people of Wales. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ull consideration must be given to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the evidence – economic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">environmental</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and social</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – relating to the exploration and potential development of the resource. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Our current precautionary planning policy position, together with controls provided through other regulatory bodies including Natural Resources Wales, provide sufficient safeguards for the environment and society. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">studying all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the available evidence and will consider bespoke research to advise on all aspects of unconventional gas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">development in Wales.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Current planning policy is sufficiently robust but we continue to monitor developments to ensure it remains fit for purpose.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Should new evidence highlight issues that need to be addressed we will review our position. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Unconventional Gas</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Shale gas is one unconventional gas which might </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e devel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ped commercially in Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – the others are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">coal bed methane and underground coal gasification. Exploration of unconventional gas is at a very early stage in the UK and there are no commercially active sites in operation currently.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Shale gas is a natural gas extracted directly from shale and is held in fractures, pore spaces and absorbed on to the organic material of shale. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hydraulic fracturing is used to stimulate the shale formations to allow the gas to escape more freely. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Coal bed methane (CBM) is gas extracted from intact coal seams</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">xtraction involves drilling down into coal seams and pumping out the groundwater. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he resultant drop in pressure enables the methane held within the coal to be released. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Underground Coal Gasification (UCG) and extraction involves the partial burning of coal underground to produce a mixture of gases. UCG is being considered particularly for utilising unmineable coal deposits and deeper seams.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The granting of UK onshore conventional and unconventional gas exploration licences, well consents and field development consents are matters for the UK Government. Any operator proposing to either explore or extract shale gas in Wales must also obtain the necessary planning permission from the local planning authority, who will determine any application in accordance with the development plan and national planning policy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DECC issues Petroleum Exploration and Development Licenses (PEDL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) in competitive licensing rounds which grant exclusivity to operators in the license area. The license does not give consent for drilling or any other operations. Existing onshore licenses already overlie a major part of the potential UK shale gas formations, including Wales.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Planning in relation to Unconventional Oil and Gas onshore in Wales is devolved, and therefore in the first instance will fall to Local Planning Authorities to determine applications in accordance with their development plan, and national planning policy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Prior to commencing exploration in Wales, any developer would have to obtain necessary planning permission from the local Welsh planning authority and demonstrate full compliance with the Welsh regulatory and environmental regime. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Natural Resources Wales is a statutory consultee in the planning process in Wales and will be consulted on all proposals for boreholes, both for the initial exploratory phase and any subsequent extraction.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Planning policy, set out in Planning Policy Wales, Minerals Planning Policy Wales and the supporting Technical and Mineral Advice Notes, sets out a precautionary approach.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Proposals must ensure all potential impacts on the environment, economy and society are appropriately mitigated and take into account climate change and greenhouse gas emissions.</span></li></ol><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><ol start="0" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Welsh Government Policy </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK Government is responsible for the granting of UK exploration licences, well consents and field development consents. The process of obtaining license consent to drill a well for shale gas is the same as that for conventional gas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our energy policy document - Energy Wales: A Low Carbon Transition (March 2012) - emphasises our ambition to move to a low carbon energy system that delivers jobs, long term wealth and benefits and supports our communities. The document also recognises the role that gas will play as we move to a low carbon energy system. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Gas is a flexible, responsive, reliable energy source with lower emissions than those from coal. Carbon capture and storage technologies will enable gas to play a longer term role in the future energy mix. This supports our current energy policy position on unconventional gas which is that we recognise there is a need to evaluate the potential of this energy source but that full consideration of all the available evidence – economic, environmental and social – is necessary relating to the exploration and potential extraction of the resource.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is supported in the precautionary approach advocated in existing national planning policy and associated planning controls. Additional regulatory processes and consents, including those undertaken by Natural Resources Wales and the Health and Safety Executive, are required prior to commencement of any drilling. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK unconventional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as exploration remains in the very early stages of development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n Wales there has been very limited deep exploratory drilling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for unconventional gas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and, to date, no hydraulic fracturing. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><ol start="0" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:13.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Welsh Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Unconventional Gas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">policy – Next Steps</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To further inform our current policy position, officials are procuring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a study </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to deliver a Wales-specific report which will:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Define the range of onshore and immediately offshore unconventional gas resource that might exist in Wales, including shale gas and coal bed methane; the geographical locations of those resources and, if available, estimates of gas-initially-in-place;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evaluate the potential impact of resource exploration and development in the identified areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Describe any limitations of existing knowledge or evidence that might need to be addressed prior to further exploration or development of the resource in the identified locations.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This Report will enable a better understanding of the geographical locations in Wales of particular interest to unconventional gas developers. It will assist in evaluating the type of unconventional gas resource that might be targeted in those areas and inform on the environmental, public health and community impacts of any such development in the identified areas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We expect the Report to highlight any associated issues unique to those locations that will need to be considered by other Welsh Government Policy teams. It will also act in informing on areas where further research might be required. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The final report is expected early in the New Year.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Welsh Ministers recognise the energy potential from unconventional gas. At the same time Minsters need to achieve a considered view on how Wales can realise economic and social benefits from an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y new industry that might </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">develop.  More specific Welsh analysis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on economic benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, technical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">issues </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(especially gas from coal seams), social benefits and gas infrastructure planning – may be needed as part of the development of an evidence-based position.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Welsh Government welcomes the recognition by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK Onshore Oil and Gas Industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the need for significant community benefits from unconventional gas projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his is offset by the lack of tax revenues to Wales from such projects and uncertainty over the scale of any employment benefits they might provide. These are just some of the issues to be addressed at these key early stages of the evolution of </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an unconventional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> gas industry in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>